```java
public class AlignmentExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String var1 = "Hello";
        String var2 = "World";

        // Using alignment specifiers
        System.out.println("<" + var1 + ">       <" + var2 + ">");

        // Using alignment() method
        System.out.println("      " + alignment(var1, 10, '<') + "     "
                + alignment(var2, 15, '>'));
    }

    public static String alignment(String str, int width, char alignChar) {
        StringBuilder paddedStr = new StringBuilder(str);
        int paddingWidth = width - str.length();

        if (alignChar == '<') { // Left alignment
            while (paddedStr.length() < width) {
                paddedStr.insert(0, " ");
            }
        } else if (alignChar == '>') { // Right alignment
            while (paddedStr.length() < width) {
                paddedStr.append(" ");
            }
        }

        return paddedStr.toString();
    }
}
```
This code demonstrates how to implement alignment using both alignment specifiers and the `alignment()` method. The `alignment()` method takes three parameters: the input string, the desired field width, and the alignment character. It returns a padded version of the input string, ensuring proper alignment according to the specified character.

